TextBlock.TextLine: C 21 march 1682
London mr Edmund Warner
my last to you was on the 7th curtt. sence non from you, because of some
amonghst the interrested in the stolen laces, could not yett send forward yd, which
now beeng brought to an end shall be dispatched p nept, wee have sustened grt
charges & trouble, & yett the states of flandres promise to assist in to restone our
loss, wee do all wee can, as long as wee see yett any prospect of recovery. I have
now desisted buying any more laces for yd acctt till finshes order, haveing in all
little more then Â£200- provided for yd acctt that com. is on the rising have
& can have no more by 8 att the forman rates, & yett I gott some allowance
for yd complaints, itt is as if all comissions came out att a time, & some work wore
dare athe 12 stivers an ell more of Æ3- & all the accordingly
& though wee keep them as low as ponr, yett finde that com. wil rise by 15 a
20p before 2 months hence, though I confess laces will be whiter & better made
this time a yeare then in the winter, which difference is no less then 5 a 64
to yd gv., as so one I receave yd commandes shall send forward what now
is ready hopeing you have well rec. the last 10 packetts
